segments.text: In your later years, you had the pool at the YMCA, and you had Sunday school classes there.
Yeah.
And any club meetings of the kind were held there.
You see, it was not too large a place.
And it was in that year that they did something with the basement.
Somebody got a lease and put a barber shop in there, and a man named Casey started a soft drink counter in there.
I didn't know students had as much money as they had.
I didn't have any money to throw around, but Casey was supposed to have a gold mine.
Did the Y there on campus operate as otherwise did?
Were there rooms for people who visited campus?
No, there was no rooms for visiting.
There was two rooms back of the foyer in the
of the main room of the YMCA was cut off from the rest of it, and the entrance was on the back side.
There was stairs on the back side.
And those two rooms up there were occupied by officers during the war activities.
There was no other rooms or facilities for guests in the YMCA.
What was the life like in the dormitories?
Was it pretty well regimented by the military?
Yes, it was military regulation.
Of course, there was a lot of extracurricular activities took place, water fights and things of that kind.
But it was one racket we had.
I remember they had a rule you had to have one light in your room, and you had to be out after taps.

Well, these electrical engineers wired those rooms so that, well, first they had shades that wouldn't let in light out the windows, because the guards, the sergeants, the army sergeants were the regular.
What's his name?
So I've just almost slipped.
The two sergeants I'd love today.
It was just the opposite of each other.
There were older people in the retired army, sergeants, and they patrolled the campus.
They weren't instructors in military science?
No, no.
They were under the commandant.
They was in charge of regulating the regulations carried out.
One of them, of course, was lights out at 1030.
But these upperclassmen, especially,
put these heavy shades on these windows.
There were great big windows in that poster hall, you know, eight-foot windows.
And then they would wire these rooms so they'd have lights all over the darn place.
But it was fixed so that when the door opened, every light went out except that one.
That was always a sneaky thing.
The wiring was covered by pendants and things of that kind.
And only the
Sophisticated electricians could do that, but otherwise you just had the one light.
I had a buggy lap robe for a table cover on a board table, and a stove.
I should have liked to get a hold of that old stove.
Only the older dorms, I think, had stoves.
Did you have a wood box in each room?
Yep, a wood box and a washstand with a bucket of water.
I've had his disadvantages.
My first roommate was a Fort Worth boy, but he had syphilis and I didn't know syphilis from anything else.
I didn't know it until later.
He had syphilis and his hair was falling out just like snowflakes and sores all over him.
And he complained that I
I said something to him.
Anyhow, he complained to the commandant that I had done something.
I forgot whether they insulted him or something.
I didn't know what he had.
I knew he had that stuff.
The sergeant called me up on the carpet, wanted to know why I wasn't getting along with this fellow, and I told him.
This fellow had some kind of disease, and he wasn't very clean.
And the next thing I knew, they had him out of school.
The hospital found out he had syphilis.
In the dormitories where you only had a washstand and a stove like that in each room, where did you bathe?
There was one room down on the first floor with showers in it.
And of course, the toilet was down there, too.
They had one room for the toilet and another room for the showers.
That was the entrance of the building down on the first floor.
So you had to run down there for showers.
You had to run down there for toilet.
And the other dormitories had toilet on the same floor.
Now, you mentioned you were in the Foster Hall as a fish.
Were you there for other years, too?
freshman and sophomore year.
My junior year I was there, but that was October.
We hotheads got enlisted.
No, that junior year I wasI don't know how I wound up in that other hall with Charlie Babcock, his
And we were working on advertising for the year's annual.
And that's when I enlisted.
What is that dormitory that's just next to Ross Hall, just north of it?
Mitchell was on this side of the street.
What was it?
And it was, oh, I didn't think I'd ever forget that.
Pfeiffer was over there somewhere.
Huh?
Pfeiffer?
Pfeiffer was one of the oldest.
Yeah.
It was one of the oldest buildings on the campus over on the other side there.
Well, anyhow, I was there for that portion of the year.
And then after that, they reserved Goodwin Hall, which is in front of Foster Hall.
When they built the new auditorium there, it was over here at the end of the street.
The first Bissell Hall, Goodwin was the older hall.
It was there when I first went.
Goodwin Hall was there.
It was a three-story in the basement.
And all of the service company was quartered in that building.
And I stayed there until the 42nd Service Company was moved out and the new one brought in.
and I was retained in that one.
And then they took over Goodwin and Ross, and then they built some barracks, and I went later into Austin Hall.
They took over all those because the student body had declined considerably.
So the Goodwin Hall and Mitchell, not Mitchell, Ross, Austin,
One other, the one I can't name, was taken over by the military.
And that lasted until 1918, November, when the armistice was signed and things moved out.
And I came back in January to enter school again.
That was the saddest part of the picture because there was a lot of bitterness.
in the atmosphere.
Between the military, I think, and this college, I think there was some friction, although I can't put my finger on it, and there was considerable friction between the college and the town.
This was right after the war?
Right after the war.
Very much unhappiness.
Of course, a lot of people in Bryan had died, and we'd lost
300 or 400 there in College Station, at least that many.
I never did have a record on it.
But I've seen the conference start to seal them for boxes waiting to be shipped out.
Well, just death from the flu there on campus.
I suppose they still do that.
If there's a death on campus, they have a military parade.
And that was always an impressive ceremony.
That happened four times while I was in college.
Now, this was the death of a student.
They'd have a military parade.
Well, now they have a ceremony which they call silver taps.
Oh, they had silver taps.
And then in addition to that, they had the parade.
Used to parade down to the railroad station to put the box on there.
Well, I don't...
There's no railroad there now.
Well, the railroad still runs through there.
It was on a freight train.
I've been there almost three years.
I don't know that there's been a death on campus.
Whenever a student is killed off campus, they have silver taps at, I believe, 10 o'clock in the evening.
We have a picture in the archives of a group of students marching down the road to Bryan.
supposedly in 1919, and someone has identified it as a student strike in 1919.
Somebody else was told me to know that after the armistice was signed, a number of students marched down to Bryan for a celebration.
Yes, they did.
So it was a celebration, celebrating the armistice.
I remember I went to class, and these students came around the corner in mobs, eight or ten deep,
And they were shouting terms which I don't remember.
But nobody went to classes.
I mean, there were no classes held because a few dumbbells like me showed up in class, didn't know what was going on.
But the student body marched, and a segment of them marched to Brian's, I remember.
But I wasn't with that group and didn't see them.
But that did happen, I'm pretty sure.
Do you remember the dormitory you lived in the last year you were there?
I lived in the dormitory next to Speza Hall.
That dormitory, if I had brought my annual down here, I could have shown you a picture.
Well, let's see.
There's, I believe, Leggett and Milner.
Leggett.
Leggett.
I believe it was Leggett.
Leggett Hall is next to the dormitory, I believe.
That's Speza, you mean?
Mm-hmm.
Leggett's next to Speezer.
Yeah, next to Speezer, yeah.
Yeah, I was in that dormitory for the last year I was there, and my roommates are both all dead.
On the mention of Speezer Hall, what was the food like in Speezer?
Well, I heard a great deal of criticism by students, but I never had any complaints about
There was more food than most humans needed, and they gobbled it up faster.
Yeah, I was dumbfounded one time.
I didn't get to a meal, and the time they marched in and out wasn't fifteen minutes.
On Thursday, I think it was, every week we had a T-bone steak that big, and bread and
pies and cakes.
I thought the meals were outstanding from my point of view, but the
A lot of people, you know, fuss.
I mean, I've seen that all over the world.
Steamships and everything else.
Well, students today fuss about the food, and there's much more variety, I imagine, than you had.
There probably was, and there probably is more variety.
I sit here the same at Tech.
I've been out there for 20 yards a year, and they complain about the food.
But any institutional food is going to have to be produced mass production, and you can't put the delicacy into it that you do in home cooking.
And a hell of a lot of them that complained about the food don't get as good food at home.
What privileges did upperclassmen enjoy that, say, freshmen didn't have?
Well, the first thing I remember is that freshmen couldn't go to town except on Saturday afternoon, and upperclassmen could go in the evening.
I don't know about any other special privilege other than they sat at a table where they got presumably preferred food, and I'm not sure they did because I never did inspect it.
It never bothered me.
Well, what about the, it was all served family style, wasn't it, as far as, what about passing the food around the table?
Yeah, they brought it, and they'd have a plate of meat for so many people that
It was family style.
You passed water around and you got your own milk and your own coffee.
I never drank coffee until my senior year.
Did upperclassmen get first choice at the meet or something like that?
Yeah, and of course there was this idea if a freshman doesn't behave properly, according to their studies, they confiscate his kush or his dessert.
things like that.

Today they have a custom, and I don't know how old it is, but an upperclassman, primarily a sophomore, will ask a freshman a question, and if he can't answer it by, say, 5 o'clock or something, then he has to give his kush to the upperclassman.
Yeah, the similar things happen, not exactly how they're sophisticated, but there'd be some of the similar lines.
In the archives, we get a good number of those questions.
I think for some of them, there just are no answers.
Ha, ha, ha.
Well, you have to give up a classroom some credit for your sophistication.
Did you have any amount of entertainment or recreation?
We talked a little bit ago about a few things in the Y and club meetings and so forth.
While we had the recorder off a minute ago, you mentioned a lecturer who was there who had an influence upon you.
Did you have much of that experience?
about once a year or something like that.
I only remember that.

Of course, every chapel day, that's Christmas, Sunday, we had a speaker from a different denomination, and some of those people were, we had to go to the chapel to get the whole core in that little building, if you remember what it looks like.
That was the old chapel building?
Yeah, the old chapel building.
Now, Diane Hall was built while you were there, and that became the new chapel then.
Yeah, the new chapel.
And while I was in the,
signaled in the last phases of that service company, I was stationed in that chapel.
We occupied that chapel.
I believe they then dubbed it the Armory, didn't they?
Yeah.
Did you ever have any movies on campus?
Yes, that came after the war, I'm pretty sure.
Yes, it came after the war.
They had an arbor out there back of the
in that open space back at the YMCA.
We had a whole couple thousand, I imagine.
They'd have pictures in there.
There were second and third-run pictures, and we had a few.
Some students put on plays.
There were several of those.
Class put them on to raise some money and things of that kind.
What sort of things?
What did they raise money for?
I think it was to buy something.
I've forgotten what that was called.
Just be a class gift to the school or something?
Yeah, something of that kind.
And I can visualize the people that were on that, and they're all dead.
They were on what?
On that program.
The only program, the only thing they had.
They're all passed out.
And they were younger people, too.
That was a time when...
The thing that dominated that period was forming of the American Veterans Association, and the commandant was married Bazell's sister.
What was his name?
Somewhere along there, Ike Ashburn.
Ike Ashburn.
I'd known him for years before he had gone to Polytechnic College in Fort Worth as a barefoot boy when I lived on Bessie Street, which was the first street leading to Polytechnic College.
I'd known him ever since he'd gone at that period of time in Polytechnic College, and he was a journalist or what we call a reporter to the public, what do you call that, communications
He was in charge of that.
On the campus?
Yes.
Or college information office or something like that.
And that was his job.
He was a big fella.
Six feet six and weighed 300 pounds and the jolliest, kindest person you ever knew.
And he and many of the faculty went out and took lessons from the Cadet Corps on drilling.
And he went off into this training camp over there, and he came back to college as a full major and made commandant at college.
And that was 1919 through 19I don't know when, how long he stayed there.
But he was the person who seemed to bring the whole
spirit of the whole thing together, absolutely.
All these men that came back, most of them were dissatisfied.
Everybody was unhappy.
I could imagine that, and I think this happened again after the Second World War, men who had interrupted their schooling to go off to the war and then come back, and they were not...
They were at odds and ends.
They didn't know what it was all about, and they were very unhappy.
I was, too.
And to put your finger on it is difficult.
But some were resentful for the treatment they'd gotten, the honor or the neglect.
Some were concerned greatly over the loss of people that they didn't have.
And all of us recognized that this was a changed environment.
It wasn't the same old easygoing.
atmosphere that we had enjoyed before, and it never was again, I don't think.
And I think once you interrupt a pattern of living, you can't ever re-establish it again.
Was there a difference, say, in the military discipline before and after the war?
There was less discipline after than before.
There was more give and take.
If you, before the war, if you failed to salute, you got reprimanded very highly.
And after that, it was all kind of slipshod.
It wasn't this great.
Was there a requirement for each cadet to speak to each other cadet as he met him on campus then?
No, they didn't.
Sometimes you did, sometimes you didn't.
But I got a taste of that in 1937.
I was down there for
I came down from the University of Pennsylvania to visit my folks in Fort Worth.
And I took that trip down to see Dean Kyle.
And I couldn't get anything done.
These students come up, introduce themselves, and then we tell them who you are.
And the first thing you know, they've taken you over.
And you don't get anything done.
And it was pleasant.
But, by George, I'd be scared to go down.
And now it's the same thing happening.
The same thing doesn't happen anymore.
Quite often you walk all the way across campus and no one will speak to you unless you speak to them first.
Well, Lord gracious, you couldn't go ten feet then in those days.
Did the cadet officers have any particular privileges over the regular cadets?
I think they did, but I can't pinpoint it.
I know that they had more freedom to do things than we did.
Did you have any favorite teachers or instructors when you were there?
Well, to tell you the truth, I think they were all my favorites.
Even the severest one, the man we had in chemistry that plunked, I think, 80% of his students for his entire career.
People disliked him, but I was assistant to a man who was in charge of keeping the chemistry building in order.
And I worked for 20 cents an hour, odd hours.
And I loved that man.
He was a little fellow, and he was very didactic.
He had everything exactly.
Chemistry was so precise, the way he presented it, the average person couldn't
conceive of it, you see.
And because the president gave us a lecture before his class started saying that it took a superior mind to, if you were proficient in chemistry, you had a superior mind.
And because I wasn't, I had an inferiority complex, although I worked in the building.
But the other chemistry teachers I thought were just, well, we were just like buddies.
And Dr. Hedges, C.C.
Hedges, I wonder if he's still living.
I'm not sure.
I would like to know.
I have thought for years I would go down to see him.
He was chemical engineer.
He was in charge of the whole chemistry division.
And Duke Thornton.
Duke Thornton is still living.
I want to see him someday.
He was just a young man in the chemistry department the last two years I was there.
The others I can remember, but I can't remember the names.
And the catalog that would have refreshed my memory I have searched all over the place for, and I have suspicion that I gave them with a ton of other stuff to the Southwest collection here.
Okay.
What was the general attitude of the students toward the administration?
And I guess this would be a dual kind of thing, one to President Bezell for the education administration and one to the commandant, to the bull for the military.
Isn't that the same?
I don't know that there was any conflict.
I can't put my finger on it.
I know I got a dream I wanted to take some plants that I had developed over in the horticulture, take them home and transplant them on this farm, and I couldn't get any.
The commandant turned me down, and I went to Wiesel's office to ask him about it, and he scolded me plenty.
But the upshot of it was, the commandant said, all right, go ahead.
Get back in three days.
And I did.
But that's the only conflict I ever had with them.
And Dr. Buzell, in later years, after that year, that was my freshman year, he was always very, very careful, very thoughtful.
And I stayed there one summer.
and got to know him and his family.
So I always felt very fond of Dr. Brazell, Dr. Hedges, Dr. Francis, and his left and right arm was Marsteller.
I had
War Courses under Marsteller, and he used to raise cane with me, and I thought he was great.
He was a rough speaking person, but he was a very gentle, fine person.
His father-in-law was Deke Fountain, who was head of English, and Dean Fountain and I were buddies.
I liked every one of my teachers, and I often wondered where they've
what's happened.
I know that Hensel and Potts in the horticulture are both gone, and I just wonder about hedges.
I'd just like to see hedges.
I'm not sure whether he's still there.

Duke Thornton, I know is, because my assistant interviewed him this summer on his career there as a teacher, and he gave us some rather interesting insights into life in Bachelor Hall, for example, and things of that nature.
Entomology, he married Miss Merriman back in, that's after I left college.
He was, in anthropology, was Bilzing.
Bilzing was a wonderful person.
I had an English teacher my senior year on public speaking, and I thought he was great.
Looking back on people like Puryear, who was assistant to the president when I went there, you know, he was a mathematician.
Oh, who was that in engineering and history?
I knew those people, but I was not necessarily a student of theirs.
But those people treated you as if you were their own kid.
That's the kind of attitude we had there.
There's a pretty close working and social relationship between the students and the faculty.
I always found it so.
Were there any girls in any of the classes that you attended?
No, whatsoever.

The only girls on the campus that year was three or four who worked in the home demonstration department who were housed in that building across the street from Speza Hall, what we call that building.
It was one of the first buildings on the campus, a four-story building.
French-type building.
What was the name of that?
I can't remember.
Gathright.
It was Gathright.
Gathright.
They were housed in that, and they came out from town on the interurban.
One girl, Ruth Cannon, was secretary to the registrar, who wasthe registrar wasI can't call his name offhand.
I can't remember it either.
preceded H.L.
Heaton, who... Yeah, well, just a minute, I'll get to it.
But Ruth Cannon, during the war, in 1918, married Runt Stangle.
And I always remember that we almost had a celebration in our company because we thought that was the greatest thing that ever happened.
Ruth Runt Stangle and Ruth Cannon got married.
That was the most beautiful couple.
And of course, Ron Stangle is the reason why I'm here.
Because out of curiosity, I came to visit Tech in 1937 to see him because I heard he was here.
